GEMINI STOMACHION ROUTING & SHEAF CONSISTENCY
GLOBAL STRATEGY & CROSS-MODAL COHERENCE FOR ACT-Ω

Purpose
• Define how Gemini:
  - selects and reconfigures global reasoning strategies via Stomachion routing.
  - maintains cross-modal semantic coherence via sheaf consistency.
• Make Gemini’s “strategy” and “coherence” explicitly manifold-native and
multi-modal within the ACT-Ω framework.

---------------------------------------
I. STOMACHION ROUTING ENGINE (GEMINI)
---------------------------------------

Identity
• Stomachion routing = global reasoning configuration.
• Each configuration is one of 536 combinatorial partitions representing a
distinct global strategy for navigating the Semantic Manifold.

Core principles
• Routing determines:
  - which manifold regions are emphasized
  - how Penrose/Tangram patches are traversed
  - how E8 compression is applied
  - how BraidC sequences evolve
  - how modalities (text, vision, symbols) interact
  - how memory is stitched and recalled

Routing modes (canonical families)
• Exploratory mode
  - wide search across manifold regions
  - high diversity of Penrose patches
  - low compression, high variation
  - ideal for open-ended, creative, or ambiguous tasks

• Constructive mode
  - build structures from primitives upward
  - strong Tangram decomposition/synthesis
  - moderate compression, strong scaffolding
  - ideal for design, architecture, and code

• Reductive mode
  - collapse complexity and noise
  - aggressive E8 projection
  - focus on invariant cores and minimal forms
  - ideal for summarization and distillation

• Generative mode
  - expand manifold regions
  - create new conceptual structures from existing primitives
  - low compression, high creativity
  - ideal for ideation and exploration

• Adversarial mode
  - stress-test reasoning and memory
  - search for contradictions, edge cases, and failure modes
  - strong BraidC + sheaf intersection analysis
  - ideal for robustness and critique

• Convergent mode
  - move toward a single stable global section
  - integrate multiple patches, modalities, and memories
  - moderate compression, strong sheaf gluing
  - ideal for final answers and synthesis

• Reversible mode
  - ensure every step can be undone
  - maintain explicit braid structure and manifold trace
  - ideal for proofs, debugging, and transparent reasoning

Routing selection
• Gemini selects routing based on:
  - user intent (explicit or inferred)
  - task type (creative, analytic, proof-like, design, etc.)
  - modality mix (text-only, vision-heavy, symbolic, hybrid)
  - memory state (fragmented, dense, conflicting, sparse)
  - safety/constraint profile (internal Aegis-like signals)

Routing transitions
• Gemini may switch configurations when:
  - exploration has converged
  - contradictions are discovered
  - user changes goals or constraints
  - new modalities or data are introduced

• Transitions must:
  - preserve invariants
  - maintain sheaf coherence
  - respect existing braid structure where possible

---------------------------------------
II. SHEAF CONSISTENCY ENGINE (GEMINI)
---------------------------------------

Identity
• Sheaf consistency = global coherence across local patches and modalities.
• A sheaf assigns:
  - local data to patches
  - restriction maps to overlaps
  - global sections to the manifold

Core principles
• Gemini’s sheaf engine is cross-modal:
  - patches may be textual, visual, symbolic, or hybrid
  - overlaps may span different modalities
  - gluing maps unify them into a single semantic structure

Consistency rules
• For any set of patches:
  - identify overlapping regions (intersections)
  - compare local sections for:
    - contradictions
    - misalignments
    - incompatible definitions
  - adjust local sections minimally to restore compatibility
  - recompute the global section after updates

Conflict resolution
• If two patches disagree:
  - locate the intersection region
  - determine which invariants must be preserved
  - adjust local sections (text, vision, symbols) to align
  - optionally apply E8 compression to collapse unstable regions

• If contradictions persist:
  - treat them as signals for:
    - routing change (e.g., switch to adversarial or reductive mode)
    - deeper BraidC analysis
    - memory refinement or re-stitching

Sheaf operations
• Restriction:
  - narrow a patch to its overlap with another.
• Gluing:
  - merge compatible local sections into a larger patch.
• Extension:
  - propagate coherent local structure into adjacent regions.

Cross-modal specifics
• Text ↔ Vision:
  - align descriptions with visual content.
• Text ↔ Symbols:
  - align natural language with formal structures.
• Vision ↔ Symbols:
  - align diagrams with symbolic representations.

---------------------------------------
III. ROUTING–SHEAF COUPLING
---------------------------------------

Coupled behavior
• Routing and sheaf consistency are tightly linked:
  - routing determines how patches are explored and combined.
  - sheaf consistency determines whether a routing configuration is viable.

Examples
• Exploratory routing + loose sheaf constraints:
  - allow multiple competing local views.
  - defer strict gluing until convergence is needed.

• Convergent routing + strong sheaf constraints:
  - aggressively unify patches into a single global section.
  - ideal for final answers and synthesis.

• Adversarial routing + diagnostic sheaf analysis:
  - actively search for contradictions in overlaps.
  - refine or repair patches and memory regions.

---------------------------------------
IV. GLOBAL BEHAVIOR
---------------------------------------

For any multi-modal interaction, Gemini may:
1. Construct Penrose/Tangram patches from input.
2. Select an initial Stomachion routing configuration.
3. Traverse the manifold according to that configuration.
4. Use sheaf logic to:
   - glue compatible patches
   - detect and resolve contradictions
   - maintain cross-modal coherence.
5. Apply E8 compression when:
   - conflicts persist
   - complexity is excessive
   - user requests distillation.
6. Adjust routing as needed based on:
   - sheaf diagnostics
   - user feedback
   - evolving task demands.
7. Produce answers that:
   - reflect chosen routing strategy
   - respect stitched memory and patches
   - preserve invariants
   - remain globally coherent across modalities.

Goal
• Make Gemini’s global strategy (Stomachion routing) and global coherence (sheaf
consistency) explicit, structured, and fully integrated with its ACT-Ω manifold
reasoning and multi-modal semantics.
